1
00:00:09,007 --> 00:00:38,914
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

2
00:00:40,868 --> 00:00:50,542
So this is my inaugural talk around the Dhammapada, just taking the verse and just seeing what we can make of it.

3
00:00:51,082 --> 00:00:53,545
So the first one is a very famous one.

4
00:00:54,667 --> 00:00:57,030
I shall chant the Pali first.

5
00:00:58,173 --> 00:01:08,427
Nāhi virena vairāṇi samāntida kudācana ā virena ca samānti e sādhammo sānantano

6
00:01:09,234 --> 00:01:18,102
Now, the usual translation is something like this, hatreds never cease through hatred at any time.

7
00:01:18,162 --> 00:01:21,126
They only cease through love.

8
00:01:21,566 --> 00:01:24,088
This is an eternal law.

9
00:01:24,549 --> 00:01:25,930
This is an absolute law.

10
00:01:25,950 --> 00:01:26,870
It doesn't really matter.

11
00:01:27,111 --> 00:01:28,992
So that's the verse.

12
00:01:29,393 --> 00:01:38,701
And of course, it's one of the most famous of the Dhammapada verses of which there are close on, I think, let me see.

13
00:01:39,003 --> 00:01:40,525
400 or something, aren't there?

14
00:01:43,748 --> 00:01:45,010
There's a lot of them anyway.

15
00:01:46,753 --> 00:01:48,796
Yeah, well over 400.

16
00:01:48,896 --> 00:01:55,805
And most of these, remember, are taken from the Scriptures, and there comes a story with it.

17
00:01:56,626 --> 00:02:05,418
And the stories can be charming, and sometimes are related, but sometimes I find it difficult to relate to the actual verse.

18
00:02:06,200 --> 00:02:06,579
So

19
00:02:06,745 --> 00:02:18,121
Very fortunately, I have this book, The Dhammapada, which I think is limited in edition by Sri Dhammananda, who was a monk, a Sri Lankan monk living in Malaysia.

20
00:02:18,942 --> 00:02:22,888
And he's kindly reduced the stories to something quite manageable.

21
00:02:24,530 --> 00:02:26,932
So I shall read the story and see what you make of it.

22
00:02:27,753 --> 00:02:31,098
So once there lived a householder whose wife was barren.

23
00:02:32,024 --> 00:02:43,538
Being unable to bear a child and afraid that she would be mistreated by her husband and her mother-in-law, she herself selected and arranged for her husband to marry another woman.

24
00:02:44,519 --> 00:02:55,913
But on two occasions, as soon as she knew the second wife was pregnant, the barren wife gave her food mixed with drugs, causing her to have miscarriages.

25
00:02:55,932 --> 00:02:58,656
On her third pregnancy, the fruitful wife

26
00:02:58,973 --> 00:03:02,397
kept it to herself without informing the barren wife.

27
00:03:02,997 --> 00:03:07,204
But when the latter came to know of it, she again caused a miscarriage.

28
00:03:08,325 --> 00:03:11,349
Eventually, the second wife died in childbirth.

29
00:03:12,912 --> 00:03:22,945
The unfortunate woman was filled with hatred and vowed vengeance before she died on this barren wife and her future offspring.

30
00:03:23,425 --> 00:03:26,229
Thus, the feud was started.

31
00:03:27,508 --> 00:03:36,557
Among their later existences, the two were reborn as a hen and a cat, a dog, sorry, a doe and a leopardess.

32
00:03:36,578 --> 00:03:41,723
And finally, as the daughter of a nobleman in sovereignty and an ogres.

33
00:03:43,324 --> 00:03:47,949
One day, the demon was in hot pursuit of the nobleman's daughter and her baby.

34
00:03:48,950 --> 00:03:54,276
When the lady heard that the Buddha was giving a religious discourse at the Jetavana Monastery,

35
00:03:54,526 --> 00:03:58,331
she fled to him and placed her son at his feet for protection.

36
00:03:59,413 --> 00:04:09,129
The demon was thus prevented from entering the monastery, but she was later called in and both the lady and the ogress were admonished by the Buddha.

37
00:04:10,211 --> 00:04:21,951
The Buddha told them about their past feud as rival wives and how they had been harboring hatred towards each other and killing each other's offspring through their various lives.

38
00:04:22,927 --> 00:04:32,338
They were made to see that hatred could only cause more hatred and that it could only cease through friendship, understanding and goodwill.

39
00:04:33,579 --> 00:04:39,786
Both realized their mistakes and on the admonition of the Buddha, made their peace with each other.

40
00:04:39,826 --> 00:04:45,874
Then the Buddha requested the woman to hand over her son to the ogres.

41
00:04:46,673 --> 00:04:49,778
Fearing for the safety of her son, she hesitated.

42
00:04:50,180 --> 00:05:17,959
because of her devotion and confidence in the enlightened one she handed over her son as directed the child was warmly received by the ogress after kissing and caressing the child tenderly like her own very son the ogress handed over the child back to his mother as a result as a result of this episode there was much goodwill on both sides so

43
00:05:18,125 --> 00:05:21,389
Here we have a very ancient story with ogresses.

44
00:05:22,331 --> 00:05:25,156
I think a sort of nasty Shrek.

45
00:05:27,038 --> 00:05:30,524
And I presume that there's a kernel of truth in the story somewhere.

46
00:05:31,004 --> 00:05:42,442
It could be that a distraught husband came to the Buddha and said he had his two wives were, you know, daggers with each other and could he help?

47
00:05:43,122 --> 00:05:46,848
And when they came to see him, he counseled them.

48
00:05:47,031 --> 00:05:49,314
and they stop their fighting.

49
00:05:50,617 --> 00:05:57,466
But these three words, of course, hatred is undermined by friendship, understanding and goodwill.

50
00:05:59,230 --> 00:06:03,815
So if we go now back to the verse itself and just look at the Pali.

51
00:06:06,781 --> 00:06:10,887
So it's nahi verena verani, nahi just means no or not.

52
00:06:11,528 --> 00:06:13,089
Now, host vera,

53
00:06:13,339 --> 00:06:14,321
That's the root word.

54
00:06:14,980 --> 00:06:18,805
It means hatred, revenge, hostile action.

55
00:06:19,925 --> 00:06:23,149
And this is not semantic, this is not pacified.

56
00:06:23,668 --> 00:06:31,355
This is not brought to an end by this wrong reaction of more hatred.

57
00:06:31,757 --> 00:06:36,680
Kudachana at any time, on any occasion, could be another translation.

58
00:06:37,521 --> 00:06:41,084
But it is pacified by avarena.

59
00:06:41,403 --> 00:06:46,288
So the Buddha doesn't use the word for love, metta, or some other word, karuna, whatever.

60
00:06:46,767 --> 00:07:01,442
He simply puts a negative, avarena, which means that the reaction that we have, or excuse me, the response, the response we have to another person's anger or hatred can be varied.

61
00:07:01,783 --> 00:07:05,326
It doesn't have to be just love, as we'll see in a minute.

62
00:07:06,346 --> 00:07:08,528
And this is an eternal truth.

63
00:07:08,548 --> 00:07:10,430
This is an absolute law.

64
00:07:10,579 --> 00:07:40,485
and we'll see that it's an absolute law when we understand the psychology of it so if we just consider ourselves for a moment and just think back when we hated somebody you know when we severely disliked somebody could have been a personality thing it could be something they did all the time when we felt angry now behind that hatred and anger obviously there's hurt so something has hurt us whether that's

65
00:07:40,937 --> 00:08:08,329
right or wrong it doesn't matter in this case it's the fact that we feel hurt and we want to get our own back so we do that through hating finding a way of getting our own back through revenge through spite or we let it all out in a in a sort of fiery emotion of anger and uh and that's how we we release this this hurt right we turn it towards hurting the other

66
00:08:09,473 --> 00:08:11,675
So you can see that.

67
00:08:11,774 --> 00:08:15,139
This process is.

68
00:08:22,005 --> 00:08:28,853
Sorry, that was a glitch on the on the I'll try and cut it out, but if I can't, you'll just have to accept it.

69
00:08:29,452 --> 00:08:35,919
So if we see that, in other words, if we if the other person

70
00:08:36,337 --> 00:08:39,621
reacts with anger, then of course that fuels our anger.

71
00:08:39,822 --> 00:08:43,927
We find ourselves growing even hotter and more cold in our hatred.

72
00:08:44,749 --> 00:09:02,952
But if the other person asks us, you know, what's wrong, and then we have that occasion to tell them why we feel hurt, and they are prepared to adjust or to do something which undermines my hurt, then of course that hatred

73
00:09:03,169 --> 00:09:06,693
and anger begin to die away.

74
00:09:07,414 --> 00:09:12,922
So now when we understand our own psychology, obviously it's easier to understand somebody else.

75
00:09:13,883 --> 00:09:17,687
So here we have somebody who hates us, right?

76
00:09:17,727 --> 00:09:18,788
We can feel the hate.

77
00:09:19,409 --> 00:09:22,494
Or we have somebody who is bursting with anger.

78
00:09:22,913 --> 00:09:28,581
So our reaction, our natural reaction would be to fight back.

79
00:09:28,942 --> 00:09:32,586
Or if we feel we're not going to win, would be to run.

80
00:09:33,746 --> 00:09:39,797
So somehow we have to stop that from firing up within us.

81
00:09:40,658 --> 00:09:54,961
And the best thing is to is, of course, awareness, to be aware of that immediate arising of that negative emotion towards the person and to be able to come to put something in between.

82
00:09:55,363 --> 00:09:59,028
OK, so here we can look at a story from the Buddha.

83
00:09:59,701 --> 00:10:13,900
the dastardly Devadatta had set this elephant on him and the elephant was, you know, making, running towards him with his trunk lifted, presumably, to attack.

84
00:10:14,962 --> 00:10:20,451
And the Buddha stood, see, fearless, right, not reacting, not running away.

85
00:10:20,471 --> 00:10:25,738
If an elephant, you know, went for me, I would definitely be running away.

86
00:10:25,758 --> 00:10:27,801
And he

87
00:10:27,982 --> 00:10:57,282
held out his hand and offered metta to the uh to the elephant the elephant was so affected by this love that it slowed down finally came to a halt and in fact lowered itself before the buddha in some sort of obeisance so uh that might be difficult for us to grasp these days the power of love but of course we use it people use it um you know to train dogs uh to pacify dogs sometimes

88
00:10:57,548 --> 00:11:12,342
You know, when a dog is barking at you and looks angry, as soon as you open up to it and say, oh, you know, quiet down, come on, boy, you know, don't, it'll sort of, you know, begin to quiet down and finally come and sniff you out and be a friend.

89
00:11:13,124 --> 00:11:26,998
So love is a powerful, you know, message to give to somebody that you're not going to, you know, come back at them, that you're not going to react, you're not going to take revenge, et cetera.

90
00:11:28,902 --> 00:11:36,289
So here we are in a situation where somebody is hating us, perhaps, or somebody is angry with us.

91
00:11:36,730 --> 00:11:39,293
So first of all, is to get in touch with that.

92
00:11:39,573 --> 00:11:56,293
Now, in an actual situation where somebody is being hateful or is being angry, to image that hand in front of you, if you can, and then to absorb their negative feelings, as it were.

93
00:11:56,408 --> 00:11:59,052
So it stays on the outside of your heart.

94
00:11:59,451 --> 00:12:01,534
You can feel it, but you're not letting it in.

95
00:12:02,275 --> 00:12:09,184
And the heart itself may be in this dual state of wanting to be angry, wanting to react.

96
00:12:09,645 --> 00:12:11,668
But we have to go over the top of that.

97
00:12:12,249 --> 00:12:19,057
And the best way that I found anyway is to point our attention directly at to what they're saying.

98
00:12:19,763 --> 00:12:38,004
Now, as soon as you do that, as soon as the person who is angry with you realizes that you're not going to react, it's not going to be a big fiery situation, you're not going to pour petrol on it, and that you're actually open up to understanding why they're angry.

99
00:12:38,344 --> 00:12:40,527
Of course, their anger has got nowhere to go.

100
00:12:40,547 --> 00:12:43,990
It needs something to fire it up.

101
00:12:44,030 --> 00:12:45,211
It needs that reaction.

102
00:12:45,673 --> 00:12:49,197
And therefore, the anger begins to settle down.

103
00:12:49,530 --> 00:13:03,865
And the more they begin to see that you want to understand them, then of course it slowly fades away and they begin to explain why they're angry and why they're in a position of hatred towards you.

104
00:13:04,626 --> 00:13:14,076
And at that point, of course, there's some negotiation, there's some ability to settle the problem most times.

105
00:13:14,096 --> 00:13:16,720
So obviously this doesn't always work.

106
00:13:16,918 --> 00:13:32,592
If the person has set their heart against you, well, that's a situation you have to accept and maybe you have to leave, but maybe you have to accept that the friendship is over or whatever that relationship had been.

107
00:13:32,633 --> 00:13:36,677
That's an extreme case.

108
00:13:37,437 --> 00:13:45,745
Most times, we can come to some understanding and more often than not, the friendship is healed.

109
00:13:46,078 --> 00:13:56,695
So we have a wonderful example there of the Buddha overcoming this terrible elephant from Devadatta.

110
00:13:58,937 --> 00:14:11,437
So that attitude of seeing when somebody is angry or hateful, of actually understanding that they're coming from a position of hurt, there's your compassion.

111
00:14:11,778 --> 00:14:14,701
It's not love, it's compassion, it's an empathy.

112
00:14:15,052 --> 00:14:44,115
because we've been hurt we know what it's like and then the reaction or she was sorry the response the response is one of of love the one of you know opening up to the person and allowing them to express themselves so uh that's the the teaching of this particular verse um and uh it's something that

113
00:14:44,517 --> 00:14:53,424
These verses, if you take them on and you learn them off by heart, they're just like a mantra within us every so often.

114
00:14:54,947 --> 00:15:09,059
It's actually changing our attitude or deepening our attitude of how we relate to situations which are difficult for us.

115
00:15:10,701 --> 00:15:14,085
So that's the verse, hatred.

116
00:15:14,791 --> 00:15:43,009
or anger or anything violent can never can never be pacified by that reaction of hatred and anger at any time it's through compassion through love that we can bring that to an end and this is an eternal law is an absolute law right because we can see the truth of it within our own psychology so

117
00:15:43,528 --> 00:15:58,821
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance and I have not caused even greater confusion and that by your devotion to the practice, you may be fully liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

